<div id='communityQuestionsWithAnswers'>
<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/1812080-does-this-biography-include-these-racist">Does this biography include these racist words from Lincoln (a much overrated civil rights hero)?

From September, 1858:

&quot;I am not, nor ever have been, in favor of bringing about in any way the social and political equality of the white and black races, that I am not, nor ever have been, in favor of making voters or jurors of negroes, nor of qualifying them to hold office...&quot;(it goes on)</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_1812080'><a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F186344.With_Malice_Toward_None">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/1812080-does-this-biography-include-these-racist">one year ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/1812080-does-this-biography-include-these-racist">See all 3 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/5711465-andrew"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1309351240i/5711465._UX100_CR0,24,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/5711465-andrew">Andrew</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">I did read &quot;With Malice Toward None&quot;: Yes it does. It was part of the Lincoln/Douglas debates for Illinois Senator. Lincoln was being race-baited by D<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">I did read "With Malice Toward None": Yes it does. It was part of the Lincoln/Douglas debates for Illinois Senator. Lincoln was being race-baited by Douglas, who laughed and spoke of "you Black Republicans." Douglas pushed fear, and spoke of sex (intermarriage) and power (black vote). So Lincoln stuck to his point for the conservative crowds that Slavery was a moral wrong, that it was a terrible slap to the Equality of the Declaration, and that it was unChristian. And Lincoln confirmed repeatedly that he was against intermarriage, and against black citizenship. <br /> Lincoln won the popular vote, but lost the election.<br /> After the 4th (of 7) debate, as he traveled by railroad to the next town, Lincoln scribbled two "fragment" thoughts. The second fragment is on a large idea then-growing in Republican circles. Lincoln looked at the slavery expansion efforts, and Compromises and Dred Scott decision and saw a designed coordinated move to subvert, to "destroy in the public mind" the basis "of free government, that all men are created equal." Oakes writes, "Yes that was the grim proslavery conspiracy Lincoln saw at work in the United States. And once the conspirators ... nationalized slavery and overthrew the Declaration of Independence, America would become a despotism based on class rule and human servitude.” <br /> Oakes published this book in 1977.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerFooter'>

